\begin_layout Subsection
Maximal entanglement
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In conventional quantum mechanics, a state 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\Psi}$
\end_inset

 is maximally entangled when equation
\begin_inset space ~

\end_inset

(27) reports its purity to be 0. Therefore, in the discrete case, states whose computed purity is a multiple of the field characteristic 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 will be incorrectly labeled as maximally entangled by equation
\begin_inset space ~

\end_inset

(27). This occurs trivially when 
\begin_inset Formula $n ~|~ p$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For example, consider the normalized 
\begin_inset Formula $n=3$
\end_inset

-qubit product state 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\Psi}$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $\ff{3^{2}}$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\ket{\Psi}=\ket{0}\otimes\left(\ket{0}-\ket{1}\right)\otimes\left(\ket{0}-\ket{1}\right)\textrm{ .}
\]
\end_inset

In this case the quantity 
\begin_inset Formula $n P_{\fh} = 3 P_{\fh} = 0$
\end_inset


\end_layout

