\begin_layout Standard
In the continuous case, the zero purity actually means every summand is 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

, i.e., 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\forall j,\forall\mu,\braket{\sigma_{\mu}^{j}}=0\textrm{ .}\label{eq:john}
\end{equation}
\end_inset

Because equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:john"

\end_inset

) avoids wrapping around when adding expectation values, it defines maximally entangled states over finite fields.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Computing some examples for various 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 and small values of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, one can verify explicitly that unit-norm product states for 
\begin_inset Formula $n=2$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $p=\{3,7,11,19,\ldots\}$
\end_inset

 occur with frequency 
\begin_inset Formula \[
(p+1)p^{2}(p-1)^{2}=\{144,14\,112,145\,200,2339\,280,\ldots\}\ ,
\]
\end_inset

and for general 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $(p+1)p^{n}(p-1)^{n}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The irreducible state counts are reduced by 
\begin_inset Formula $(p+1)$
\end_inset

, giving 
\begin_inset Formula \[
p^{2}(p-1)^{2}=\{36,1764,12\,100,116\,964,\ldots\}\ ,
\]
\end_inset

and in general for 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-qubits, there are 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{n}\left(p-1\right)^{n}$
\end_inset

 instances of product pure states.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Repeating the computation, we find maximally entanglement states with frequencies for two qubits of 
\begin_inset Formula \[
p\left(p-1\right)\left(p+1\right)^{2}=\left\{ 96,2688,15\,840,136\,800,\ldots\right\} \ .
\]
\end_inset

The irreducible state counts for maximal entanglement are reduced by 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(p+1\right)$
\end_inset

, giving for 
\begin_inset Formula $n=2$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula \[
p\left(p^{2}-1\right)=\left\{ 24,336,1320,6840,\ldots\right\} \ .
\]
\end_inset

For three-qubits, there are 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{3}\left(p^{4}-1\right)\left(p+1\right)$
\end_inset

 instances of pure maximally entangled states, while the general formula for four-qubit states remains unclear.
\end_layout

